WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Okay, is that too loud? Is that good?

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Thank you all so much for coming to this talk today. I'm going to be talking about Shiny, which is a Python web application framework.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:23.000
And I think sort of where I wanted to start this talk was to talk about sort of how data scientists kind of actually deliver value.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:32.000
So my background is as a data scientist. I've been working there for about a year or so until I moved over to Plosset to do software engineering.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:37.000
And what I kind of always notice is that data science has kind of a last mile problem.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:44.000
You do a ton of work to gather data, to get access to that data, to find a place to analyze it, do the analysis, build the model.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:51.000
And then at the end of the day, you kind of have to deliver it. And that point of delivery is where your company starts getting value from your work.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.000
But that point of delivery is really difficult. You often have to wait for, I think especially in the Python world,

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:06.000
you don't have to wait for a quote-unquote real web developer to come in and build a product that is going to deliver your analysis to stakeholders.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
People actually pay your bills. This is really expensive. You know, as you saw in PyBio, which had a great case study,

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:19.000
it's really expensive to hire somebody from outside your company, find web developers in your current company, get it on their roadmap.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.000
It takes forever to do this type of work by the nature of the frameworks that those people use.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:32.000
And most importantly, it's often incorrect. In order to deliver a really good data science product, you need to have intuition about your data.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:39.000
And a generic web developer often doesn't have that. So they might present the data in such a way that it's confusing or inaccurate.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
And then you have to go through this whole process again.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
So why can't we just do it ourselves?

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:51.000
I think the main reason why we can't do it ourselves is that whenever you're delivering one of these products, it's kind of like getting a puppy.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.000
You put it in front of people, they like it, they want more from it, and it starts to grow.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:04.000
So you need to have a framework which can grow with that problem. And most of the available application frameworks don't.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Just to give you a kind of example of this, when I was at SoQer, the data science was putting together a feature management API.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:17.000
The idea behind this was it was a central source where everyone in the company could get information about our machine learning features,

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:22.000
where they came from, what they were called, how they fit together.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:27.000
It was developed by a data science team and was important. It was something that was going to be used by more or less the whole company.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.000
But it needed a front end.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:33.000
So when we looked at all the tools that we had available to ourselves, none of them really fit.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:40.000
They were either kind of too hard for the data science team to use, or they were too limited for that product to grow where we thought it would grow.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So we needed something which could grow.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Streamlet looked pretty fragile in terms of re-executing everything all the time.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:54.000
When we looked at Dash, this restriction on having only stateless components, so you couldn't really share data between graphs or between graphs and plots,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
seemed pretty awkward.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
And none of us knew JavaScript, so we were kind of stuck.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:06.000
We ended up needing to basically wait, I think, nine months before we ended up getting the hire approved, hiring the person, onboarding that person, and building that application.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
So Shiny is designed for that problem. It's designed to grow.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:16.000
And this makes it a little bit difficult to talk about in a demo.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Because I can't show you a big application that's going to grow in 48 minutes.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
And that's really where this framework shines.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:28.000
It's very simple to get started, but it has all the tools you need to build full products.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.000
It's all in Python. There's an R version. There's the historical version of Shiny.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Shiny was rewritten last year in Python.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
It's easy enough to build a prototype, but it has the tools that you need to build a product.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:41.000
But showing that growth is complicated.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:45.000
So what I'm going to do instead is I'm going to talk about Shiny's algorithm.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:51.000
And try to develop a little bit of an intuition about how Shiny actually does this work.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.000
What's special about it, and how it works.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.000
So let's take a look at an example.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
So this is a three-page app. I'm just going to tell the story for each page.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.000
So it just shows a little bit of how these grow.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.000
So this is a kind of example of a basic training dashboard.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
You know, maybe I fit a model.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
I want to just expose it to stakeholders so that they can check their accounts that are going to be hitting this model.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Make sure the model performs as well for that particular account as it does in general.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
So I have two little plots. It shows a model score and a little ROC curve.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:26.000
And the user can change what plot they want.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.000
So what's interesting about Shiny is that when I update this metric,

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:34.000
the only plot that actually fires or changes is this one.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
Nothing happens over here.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:41.000
But if I change the account, since both of them depend on that account slider, both change.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So it's minimally re-rendering things.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:49.000
It's only re-rendering the parts of my application that need to change in response to a particular user action.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
But how does it do that?

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
So this is the full code that generates those plots.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And one of the things, when you look at this code, if you have some background in web development, it's a little weird.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
There's no callbacks here.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
They're in a state.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:10.000
So how is it that Shiny is figuring out how to render things in this really efficient way?

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Another way of putting this is we told Shiny what to do.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.000
We said, here's how you make these plots.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
But we never told it when to do it.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
But somehow Shiny knows when to do it.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
And it more or less always gets that right.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
How do other frameworks accomplish this?

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:29.000
So the bluntness approach is great, especially for simple applications, but pretty blunt for larger ones.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.000
Where it just re-renders everything.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.000
Just start from the beginning, re-render everything.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
So I don't need to figure out how things should update.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
I just re-render everything.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
And you can kind of get more into the weeds of state and caching later.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
But in the beginning, that's kind of how it works.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
And most other frameworks use event handling.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:50.000
What event handling is, is you, the programmer, define when things should fire.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
When your renderers should fire.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:57.000
So you say, when this button changes, on click, on change, do this action.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
And it has some problems.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
I think the first one is you have to do it.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
So as a data scientist, that's a little much, I think.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Doing it and doing it correctly is hard.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.000
It's pretty easy to get it wrong.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:13.000
If you fire callbacks in the wrong order, you update state in one part of your application and not another.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:18.000
You can get these kind of pernicious bugs where you show the user the wrong value.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.000
And importantly, it's really hard to tell when you get it wrong.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.000
Sometimes you need to kind of get into a particular state in testing to trigger that sort of value.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:29.000
So usually when event handling goes wrong, you don't get a failure.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.000
You get an incorrect value somewhere deep in your application.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
My favorite example of this is Slack.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.000
So about every three weeks, I get an undismissible Slack notification that says,

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
You have activity. Go deal with your activity.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And I click and I don't have any activity.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.000
And I just know, deep in my heart, somewhere in the Slack event handling artifice,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.000
somebody in there has forgotten to update a state variable.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
Or she's forgotten to retrieve a state variable.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
And I'm the one that has to suffer for it.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
So what's a better way?

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.000
A better way is, you know, you can think about DAGs, right?

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:06.000
So rectidacyclic graphs are great because you know that for any particular upstream change,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.000
which nodes need to change downstream, right?

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:10.000
And that's wonderful.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:14.000
This is something you use in make files, Airflow, all over the place, right?

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:18.000
It's a very good way of figuring out that problem of what needs to re-execute.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
But the problem is you still have to write this.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
If you write this wrong, your application is going to be wrong.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So is there a way we can maybe avoid writing this at all?

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
So here's Shiny's strategy.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Shiny's strategy is to infer all the relationships between your component from your application.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.000
And use that inference to build a computation graph.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
And use that computation graph to minimally re-execute your application.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:43.000
Right?

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:44.000
Okay.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
So telling you that I'm doing this kind of magic inference,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:51.000
I would just suggest that that should create a little bit of suspicion, right?

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.000
Because oftentimes you get these inferences and they're like 85%, right?

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
And that's much worse than just not doing it at all, right?

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
I don't want to have an inference if it's not rock-solid, right?

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.000
And so this is a good face.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
It's a good face to make.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:06.000
I'm Larry.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
So this has to work all the time.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
100% of the time.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
Because if it misses one, then you're not going to be able to trust it.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
And you're going to have to do the event handling anyway.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:20.000
And if you can't trust that inference, it's not useful to you.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So one question then is, like, okay, how would we do this, right?

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:24.000
Let's just start from scratch.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:25.000
Like, how would you do this?

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.000
And one answer you might think of is, well, we could analyze the source code, right?

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
So I have these inputs here.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
Those inputs are likely user inputs.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
So maybe I could read all the source code.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:35.000
I could parse it.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:36.000
Find all those inputs.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And use those to draw that down.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
And you could sort of think, okay, that might work.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.000
It would be hard.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:42.000
Right?

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:43.000
But it might work.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:44.000
But it won't work.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:49.000
And the reason it won't work is because Shiny allows dynamic user interfaces.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:51.000
So this is a to-do list.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
So if I, like, say buy groceries, I can add a bunch of these tasks.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
I can complete these tasks and clear them.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And things go away, right?

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:08.000
So at any given point in this application, the application's state depends on all the things that the user has done up until that point.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:09.000
Right?

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And the reason we're doing that is that this particular application state is not in the source code.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:14.000
Right?

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.000
And it's very difficult, therefore, to use static code analysis to get that application state.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.000
So it's not going to work.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.000
Instead, what Shiny does is runtime tracing.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:30.000
So at runtime, while your application is running, it just watches what all of the different components ask for.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And it writes that down.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
It says, okay, you asked for this thing last time.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:39.000
I'm going to know that when that changes, I'm going to ask you to re-render.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:40.000
Right?

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:41.000
Because I remember that you asked it.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
I don't really care about what's happening in the code.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:45.000
I just know that you made a request for this thing.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.000
And that thing is a reactive thing.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
So I'm going to, like, just keep track of that.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.000
But what happens inside is not really my business.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
So how does this kind of just walk you through a really basic example?

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
So user asks for this output.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
So this is an output on the screen called text.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
It's the ID.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
Shiny then goes and finds the rendering function that matches that ID.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
It fires it.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
And when it fires the rendering function, you see there's this input call.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:15.000
So that's a call out to an input from the UI.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
And then Shiny goes and gets the value of that UI.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
It records all of those steps, right?

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
And in a simplified way, you get this little graph.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
So you get one input to one output.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Most of the rest of this talk is just going to be about these beautiful little mermaid graphs.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.000
So let's just refresh our memory about what this looks like.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:41.000
So I have two inputs and two outputs, like the count input, the metric input,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:46.000
and then the model metrics plot and the distribution here.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
And when Shiny starts out, this is all it knows.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
It just knows that there are four things.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
Two of them are inputs and two of them are outputs.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
It has no idea about any of the relationships between them.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
And so it's like, okay, I don't have any idea what's going to happen.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
So let's just try to get one of these outputs.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.000
I'm going to pick the metric plot.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
So it calculates the metric plot, and then the metric plot goes out

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
and requests the selector and the account selector.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
Those are the two things it needs to generate its plot.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
Shiny does that and draws these two lines.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
And the distribution plot fires, and that only needs the account selector.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
So the model metric doesn't matter.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
And there we have our graph.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
No staticated code analysis is required.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:29.000
So when the account changes, Shiny does something called invalidate.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
And what that means is it tells the downstream dependencies,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
you're not good anymore, you need to recalculate.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
So it invalidates those two outputs.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.000
And when things are invalidated,

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:43.000
it just forgets everything that it knows about those relationships.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
Because, again, this is all happening at runtime.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
So while those relationships that was the relationships before

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
might not be the relationship now when I recalculate.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
So it recalculates, and in this case it gets the same graph.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
So it gets these two inputs, tries to calculate the distribution,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
gets the account selector, and we're back.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
If the metric changes, though, something different happens, right?

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
Because the metric only has one child node.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
So that's the only one it invalidates,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
but the distribution plot doesn't need to invalidate, right?

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
It didn't depend on it, right?

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
So it's still good, it doesn't need to recalculate.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
We still forget the dependencies from the invalidated nodes,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
and then recalculate it.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
So go get the two values, and we're done.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
So this is the kind of secret of how Shiny is able to let you build

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:35.000
very performant applications with very low workload as a developer.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:40.000
I don't need to, as a developer, keep track of this graph, really, in any way.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
I need to tell Shiny, I need to declare to Shiny,

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
this is how these things should be drawn.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
But then Shiny is able to infer from that, as that application runs,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
how those things should be re-rendered.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
So I'm stepping one level up in abstraction.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:58.000
I'm not doing the cooking, I'm setting the menu.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.000
And this frees you from a lot of work as a web developer.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.000
So this graph we showed, everything was the same.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
It came to the same conclusion, so it seems like a little bit of a lot of work,

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
but it's forgetting everything.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
But Shiny actually can do graphs that do change,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
and this is pretty common.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
So here I have a really simple example where I have one slider.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:23.000
I have a button which tells Shiny which slider it should use,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
it should listen to.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
And when I change this slider, nothing changes.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:31.000
But if I want to change slider one, the text changes.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
And if I switch this, and I go to slider two,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:40.000
now slider one is ignored, and slider two responds.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
And here's the code that's doing that rendering.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
And basically it's just a simple conditional,

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
where if it's slider one, I'm returning one slider value,

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
and otherwise I'm returning slider one.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
So again, Shiny knows nothing about this application,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
it just knows that there are three inputs and one output.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
It tries to calculate the text output.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
Initially, the first thing it needs is, like,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
I'm doing that conditional, which slider should I call in,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
go get the button's value.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And then it knows to go get slider value, and we're finished, right?

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.000
It never got to input slider two.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:15.000
So then when slider two changes, nothing happens, right?

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
And I just want to pause for a second and explain why that's correct.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
So when we ran that first function,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.000
it said it came to its conclusion without ever asking for the value of slider two.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:31.000
What that means is that for all possible values of slider two,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
this output is the same.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
And if that's true, that means that if slider two changes,

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
we can just ignore it, right?

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:41.000
For all possible values of that, the output ended up being the same.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.000
So if slider one changes, this is kind of the same process

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:47.000
where the text output invalidates, it goes and gets the button,

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:51.000
the button's still slider one, so it changes to slider one.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:55.000
But if the buttons change, when it invalidates the text output

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
and goes and gets the new value of the button,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
which it says, go look at slider two,

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
this time it's going to get slider two, right?

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
And we have a different graph.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
So that's kind of why we have this process of things changing,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
because the reactive graph is going to change

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
over the course of that user's application.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And again, for those dynamic UI elements,

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
where you're adding and removing things,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
where things are changing based on other values,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
this is really important.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
Because you might actually add or remove nodes from this graph

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:25.000
based on what has happened previously in that session.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:31.000
Any questions about that?

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
Okay, that's either very clear or incredibly unclear.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
So let's power through.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.000
So what's great about this pattern is that it scales.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
So every single Shiny app uses this exact pattern.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:47.000
There's no way of developing complex Shiny apps

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
versus simple Shiny apps.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
They all fundamentally use this type of transparent reactivity.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And you can kind of imagine how this scales, right?

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
DAGs are very efficient at rendering.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
So if I have lots and lots of components,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
assuming that Shiny is going to be able to use this same process

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
to put it into a DAG,

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
it's going to be able to render those very complicated applications.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
This works for dynamic UI.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
And lastly, it's lazy.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
So because it's starting out at the bottom of that graph,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
where the user is asking for something,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
if something is hidden from the user,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
it never gets calculated

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.000
until the user actually goes and asks for it.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
So I'll give you a kind of example of this.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
So here I have these, like, three tabs

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
with stuff happening on them.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
But the training dashboard is the only one that actually

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
has the application that's happening,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
because the user hasn't asked for anything on these background tabs.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
So while Shiny has attached them to the DOM,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:40.000
they're not calculated.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
Okay.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:46.000
So that's why we've kind of been working with shallow graphs.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
Like, everything is...

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
all the inputs are being directly consumed by an output.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
And that's great.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
In these simple cases, it works really well.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
But it's pretty limited, right?

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Particularly, like, each of those rendering functions

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
is kind of working like that.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
They're doing all of the work they need to calculate,

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
and they're not really able to share common calculations.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
So there's kind of repetition.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
There might be repetition between them.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
And that kind of limits its efficiency.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:14.000
So we have a concept called a reactive calculation.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
And what a reactive calculation does

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
is it's basically a way of creating a function

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
in this reactive paradigm.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
So it creates a calculation

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
whose results can be used by other functions,

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
either other reactive calculations or other renderers.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
It basically adds depth to a graph.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
So let's take a look at this model monitoring.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
So this is an example of it growing.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
Everyone's happy with my model. I've deployed it.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
Now I need to keep track of it.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
And this is a production. There's lots of data coming in.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
So I need to have some way of basically, like,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
taking a sample and investigating it.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.000
So the idea here is that I'm able to specify a date range,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
create a sample size,

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
and this is going to query a database

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
to bring in my sample.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.000
But I can still look through these accounts in memory.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
So this will pull the data from all the accounts that I have.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
And so that accounting will be really fast,

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:02.000
even if the sample data is a little slow.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
So what do I want from this?

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:09.000
So I want to query that database to get my sample.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:13.000
And then later on, I want to filter that sample in memory.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
I don't want to have to go back to the database.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
I want to have that filter in memory.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.000
I want to send that same data to the two different functions

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
without doing the filter again

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
and without doing the sampling again.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.000
I want to cache the results of all of those queries.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
I want to invalidate the cache

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
whenever its upstream dependencies change.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
And I don't want to do any thinking or work.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
I don't want to have to worry about this at all.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
I'm a data scientist.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
I'm not good at that stuff.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:44.000
So I just want to have it handled formally.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
And so this is, I think,

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
one of the core things about Shiny,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
is that there are other Python application frameworks

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
that can do some of these things,

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
but none of them can do all of them.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
In particular, I think none of them can do 4, 5, and 6 together.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:00.000
So how does Shiny do 4, 5, and 6 together?

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
So we have this ReactiveCalcDecorator.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
And what that does is it caches its value.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
So whenever it runs, the first time it runs,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
it caches its value.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
So you can call it repeatedly.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
And it sticks that reactive calculation

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
in the same reactive graph.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.000
So it discards the cache whenever it's upstream,

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
whenever it's invalidated,

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
and it tells its descendants

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.000
that it's been invalidated, just like the inputs did.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.000
So this is how you might code that example.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
So you see we have two reactives here.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:32.000
One is the sample data that handles that query step,

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:34.000
querying the database.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:37.000
And then the second one is this filter data

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
that does the account holder.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
And how you call these

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
is you basically just call them as functions.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
So in the filter data, it's calling sample data.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
And then when I have this plot score,

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
it does its calling filter data.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
So I have these little hexagons

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
to kind of indicate reactive calculations.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
But again, Chiny, when it starts,

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
it doesn't know how these things are related.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
It just knows that there's three inputs,

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
two reactive calculations, and two plots.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
And it starts from the bottom

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
and just tries to calculate the model score.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.000
So it calculates the model score.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
Model score goes and says, I need that filter data.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
Filter data requires the account

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.000
and the sample reactive calculation.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:18.000
That sample reactive calculation then runs,

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
and it says, oh, I need the dates and the sample size

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.000
in order to get a sample.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
It does that, passes the data down to model score,

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
plot's produced.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.000
But when the API response calls,

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
this just needs the filter data.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
It needs the exact same thing as model score.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
So nothing is calculated.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
No filtering is done, no sampling is done.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
It just goes and retrieves the cache.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
So that's how the cache account works.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
When the validation works,

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
if the account changes,

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.000
it does the same thing.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
It tells its dependents you're invalid.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
So filter is invalid, it needs to recalculate.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
Filter goes and tells its children,

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
hey, you're invalid too.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
And they forget everything that they knew

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
about their previous dependencies.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
And the same process goes.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:06.000
Model scores runs, gets filtered.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
This time it doesn't take a fresh sample

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
because the upstream of sample hasn't changed.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
And that's important because

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.000
if you're doing these sampling operations,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.000
you want to take your sample once

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
and interrogate that same sample

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
in many places.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
So if you're not doing this type of caching with sampling,

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.000
you might end up with this place where

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
whenever I change the account,

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
I'm taking a fresh sample and getting

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
an inaccurate intuition about it.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
Because it might be one sample shows one value,

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.000
another sample shows another one,

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.000
and I really want to investigate that same sample.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
An API response does the same thing

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
as always does,

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:43.000
When something further upstream changes,

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.000
the whole graph gets invalidated.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
So when sample size changes,

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
we do need to go get a new sample

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
from the database.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
So sample invalidates, filter invalidates,

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
plots invalidate,

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.000
and we're back to our initial state

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
not knowing anything about this application,

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
and go out and get our same inputs and outputs.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
And an API response, again,

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:05.000
just gets its cache validated.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.000
So this lets you build up

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:09.000
pretty arbitrarily complex applications

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
because you can stack these reactive calculations

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
as deep as you need to.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
And they're always going to do

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
effectively the minimum amount of work

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
that they need to

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.000
in order to generate your application.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
So whenever you're developing tinyapps,

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
it's pretty important to stick to a pretty strict

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
do-not-repeat-yourself rule,

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
both because it keeps your code in one place,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
but also because by avoiding repetition

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
with reactive calculations,

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
you actually make your whole application

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.000
much more efficient.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:40.000
Any questions about that?

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.000
Yes?

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:46.000
How are you...

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.000
So what criteria are you using

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
to determine if data has been cached or not?

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.000
Are you looking at the values that were retrieved

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
by the input function?

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.000
No, we're not.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
We're just using a graph.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
So we don't know...

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
And this is also important because we're not

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
caching that to disk or caching that to memory,

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
like caching the whole big data frame.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
We're just pulling the object in memory

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.000
and knowing that...

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.000
The way we're determining whether it needs

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
to change or not is basically

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
did my parent nodes change?

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
Okay, so if I ask for count A,

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.000
then B, then A,

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
the whole thing triggers again?

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.000
Yes.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.000
Because again, Shiny isn't like...

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:28.000
So there are ways of doing that type of caching

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.000
in Shiny, too, where you are sort of saying

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
I want to just check the value.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:34.000
But the problem is that that check isn't free.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
So if I'm doing that hashing,

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.000
I have to do a hash and a hash comparison,

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
which if it's a giant dataset,

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:42.000
might actually be more expensive than

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.000
doing the filter twice.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.000
So you can do that, but it's not automatic.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
The automatic thing is that we're just going to hold

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:50.000
the result of that filter calculation

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.000
and determine based on the graph.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:54.000
Great question.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:56.000
Okay, so reactivity is a great default.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.000
This idea of just letting you infer

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.000
how things should work,

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
manage state and caching,

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
and validation for you.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
But it's not the only thing.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.000
Not everything fits this pattern perfectly.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.000
So sometimes you actually do want to specify

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
I want this to happen when that happens.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
You do want to do a bit of unhandling.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000
So an example is batching inputs

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
or triggering a side effect.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.000
And event-driven programming

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.000
is not all bad.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:24.000
The problem is when you use it for everything,

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.000
you run into these mistakes.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
So an example of this is,

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
again, my application growing.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
So here maybe I've determined that

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.000
my model isn't doing very well,

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.000
so I need to do some data updating.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.000
And I have these little buttons where I'm just saying

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.000
I'm reading something, and that looks like electronics.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:42.000
This is obviously not the thing

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:44.000
that people dream of

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.000
when they're doing data science school,

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:48.000
but it turns out it's super important.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.000
And I won't bore you

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:52.000
pretty much with this,

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.000
but every time I change this,

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.000
it's basically like writing an annotation

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.000
to a CSV file.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
And that doesn't fit very well

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
with this idea of a reactive graph.

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.000
I don't really want the value.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
I want to trigger some sort of thing

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
outside of my application.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
Update database, deploy model, something like that.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
So we don't want this to react automatically.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.000
We want to specify the user

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.000
what happens when that button is clicked.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.000
So we have this decorator called reactive effect.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
There's two ones that go together often,

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
reactive effect and reactive event.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.000
So reactive effect

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.000
indicates that this is a side effect,

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.000
so I shouldn't return a value

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
from that function, I just want the side effect to occur.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
And reactive event

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
says what's the trigger

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
for that event. And this can be

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
inputs, it can also be reactive calculations.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:40.000
And the one key point here

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.000
is I'm referring to this

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.000
input as an object.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
This is a callable object, so when you

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
want the value, you call it.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
But if you just want to say, pay attention to this thing

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.000
whenever this thing changes,

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
fire this function,

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.000
that's a raw object.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:58.000
And then we have this body of the function

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
that defines what that calculation is.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
So this is how you would do

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
something like a side effect, or

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.000
you know, an API call, or something like that.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
Or a post-interim API, or like,

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:10.000
something like that.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:12.000
So reactive event can also be paired with

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
renderers or reactive calcs.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:16.000
If you don't, for whatever reason,

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.000
set Chinese inference isn't working,

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:20.000
you want to override it and say,

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.000
an example is you have five inputs

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.000
in a form, and you want them all to

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:26.000
only go together with a

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.000
bad button input, that would be a case where you would

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:30.000
want to maybe have a reactive event

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
on top of your reactive calc.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.000
It says, ignore all the other dependencies

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.000
and just use this one. This is the only dependency

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
you should use.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:40.000
And the way I think about this is it's kind of like adding

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.000
event-driven chocolate chips to the broader

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.000
reactive cookie. So you don't want to do this

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.000
all the time. Most of the work

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
is reactivity, transparent reactivity,

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
but you sometimes do want to have these little

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
event-driven patterns in there.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.000
And one thing I have found,

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:56.000
especially from people who are

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:58.000
transitioning from an event-driven

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:00.000
front-end framework, especially JavaScript,

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.000
is they're

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:04.000
kind of uncomfortable by how little work they have

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.000
to do in Chinese, so they kind of start using

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
reactive events everywhere.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
And I would sort of say that's a cold stop.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
You notice yourself doing that,

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.000
just relax. You don't actually need to do

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.000
that much work. It is normal to feel

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.000
that way.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.000
So yes, you want to try to rely on reactivity,

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:22.000
but you need to override it for whatever reason.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.000
Actually, that's the way to go.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
And the last thing is that

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
reactive events and reactive effects

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
and reactive calculations, basically the

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:32.000
intuition there is reactive effects are for

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.000
side effects, reactive calculations are for

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.000
values. So side effects are things that

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.000
happen outside of the world of your application,

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.000
like updating a database or writing to a

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:42.000
CSV file, playing model,

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.000
something like that. And reactive calculations

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.000
are for values, like

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.000
calculation, as it was right there in the name,

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:50.000
fetching a data from a database, that's usually

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
you want the value of that data, you don't want

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:54.000
the act of fetching it

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.000
for filtering the data frame.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:58.000
So one thing I'll just ask you,

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
I'm going to be positive, is you should

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.000
think a little bit about this pattern and ways

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:04.000
that it would fall down. We have a lot

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
of other functions that I'm not going to get to

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:08.000
today to kind of cover those. So reactive

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
isolate is for event cycles in your graph.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:12.000
If you need to include data,

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:14.000
like a database or some external

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:16.000
object as part of that reactive graph, like you have

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:18.000
an airflow pipeline that's dumping

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.000
a file and you want your app to always react

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
to the changes in that file,

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
reactive pull or reactive file

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
reader do that. If you

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
want something to react to time, basically

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.000
like invalidate every five minutes on a cycle,

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.000
we have invalidate leader.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:34.000
And you can store variables

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.000
with reactive values. So if you ever have

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.000
a side effect that you want to then

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.000
trigger a reactive, the rest of your

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.000
reactive value is how you do that.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:46.000
So in summary, Shiny creates very

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:48.000
performant apps with very little work.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:50.000
And this is its killer feature.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:52.000
And as your application grows,

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:54.000
that's more and more valuable. It's valuable

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:56.000
at the beginning, but especially when you're managing

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
larger, complicated applications,

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
it's a lifesaver.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.000
This algorithm is very elegant, I think,

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:04.000
but it's not magic. There's nothing that's

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.000
not difficult to understand here,

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.000
and there's nothing that you can't really develop

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:10.000
an intuition about.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:12.000
And then overall, I would say it's important

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:14.000
that whatever framework you pick, that your

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:16.000
users are guiding how your application looks

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:18.000
and feels, not the limitations of the framework.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:20.000
You want to have a framework that gives you

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.000
the flexibility that you need to really accomplish

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
the things that your users want you to do.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:26.000
And choosing a framework that you grow is super important.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:28.000
So thank you.

