Oh yeah, go ahead.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.000
Just to make sure I follow you.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:58.000
So that graph,

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:00.000
does that basically get rebuilt every time

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:02.000
one of the

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:04.000
downstream inputs changes?

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.000
Yes. So anytime something

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:08.000
happens with a graph, parts of it get rebuilt.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
So the parts that are invalidated get

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:12.000
rebuilt. The parts that are not invalidated,

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
you know that those values are all good, so you don't

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:16.000
need them.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.000
Yeah.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:30.000
So there's two, I would say, so the question is

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:32.000
shiny for R and shiny for Python, do they have identical

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:34.000
feature sets? So there's two parts to that.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:36.000
So one is the shiny core

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:38.000
library, and then the second one is the broader

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
shiny community. So I would say

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.000
right now, the core library for

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.000
shiny for R and shiny for Python are pretty close.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:46.000
The main features are

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
markless state, some things

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:50.000
like that, but in terms of the main features,

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:52.000
they're pretty neat, they're very similar.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.000
The community is, if the newer package, the

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:56.000
community is much smaller, so we don't quite have the same

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
rich feature extensions.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:00.000
So we have a plan of

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:02.000
continuing to bring the core library closer

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:04.000
to it, but most of the stuff that we have now

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:06.000
that's missing are things

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.000
that new users

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:10.000
don't use all that much, so our focus

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:12.000
is more on improving the

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.000
early experience of shiny, which

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
there will be some divergence, I think,

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
of those two libraries,

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:20.000
because they are just different discrete functions.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
But yeah, they're pretty close.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:24.000
And shiny for Python also has most of the

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:26.000
BSL components as well, so they're

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:28.000
the same library.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:30.000
Yeah.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
How customizable is the front end?

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.000
Like if you wanted to do styling?

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.000
Yeah, so fully.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.000
So you can do,

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
so all of those,

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:42.000
all of our inputs have just basically

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:44.000
